<b>few tips that worked for me. - </b>7/24/01 10:15:14 AM<br>~ <b>Wayoff</b><blockquote>I found the same thing was happening with hill giants...once charmed they would wander off, leaving me having to chase them with the other mob following me.<br><br>I found that making a few /pet social keys helped tremendously.<br><br>/pet guard here   : this works much better than /pet sit down to keep a pet still<br><br>/pet follow me     : helps with those running giants.<br><br>you need to hotkey these socials and hit them almost right after you have charmed the mob..but it does save time in the long run as you won't need to chase after your pet to send it onto an angry mob.<br></blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>More uses for Charm.... - </b>7/15/01 12:22:36 AM<br>~ <b>Melpomene Mouseai</b><blockquote>Not only does this delightful song work well on Hill Giants, it also works quite well in Sol B. <br><br>While I must admit I have done Hill Giants as well, kobolds provide a bit more exp (depending on your level range).  The same method is used... start by using your Curtailing Chant to lower the mob's Fire Resist (esp in sol B) then deal out some damage with Tuyen's.... after that cast charm and sick your slightly ruffled pet on another unsuspecting kobold.  A Greater Kobold Shaman is generally my charmed pet of choice, as they tend to deal out the most damage, but any kobold will do nicely. <br><br>Once their duel to the death is finished, you have but a few ticks of Tuyen's and a few measly hits and superb experience is yours.<br><br>This strategy in Sol B is best played out in the circle room... it is very close to the zone and is also in the middle of a few spawning locations for both shamans and greater kobolds. <br><br>Happy Hunting! <br><br>(*cheers for her buddy Fyr for his great charm guide as well*) :)</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
